description: From Middle English endyng, endinge, endunge, from Old English endung, ġeendung (“ending”), equivalent to end +‎ -ing. Cognate with Dutch ending (“ending”), German Endung (“ending”).

examples: The book has a happy ending.
The film has an unexpected ending.

entries.meaning: (grammar) The last morpheme of a word, added to some base to make an inflected form (such as -s in "dogs").
examples: Spanish verb forms have different endings depending on the tense, mood and person.

description: From Middle English ending, endyng, endende, from Old English endiende, from Proto-Germanic *andijōndz, present participle of Proto-Germanic *andijōną (“to end”), equivalent to end +‎ -ing.
